Recommendations:
We reiterated our recommendations in the previous year that Management:
Formulate strategies to provide the necessary workforce for conducting the inventory-taking and maintaining property cards and other pertinent PPE records;
Expedite the creation of an Inventory Committee to take charge of the physical count of PPE and the submission of RPCPPE according to the guidelines prescribed in the aforementioned COA circular;
Require the Municipal Accountant and the GSO to update the PPE Ledger Cards and Property cards and ensure regular reconciliation these and other related records;
Instruct the Property Division/Unit to identify the person/s accountable for the non-existing/missing PPEs based on the Property Acknowledgement Receipts (PARs), Property Cards (PCs), and other available property records, and thereafter issue demand letters to produce the missing PPE; and
Direct the Inventory Committee, the Property Division/Unit, and the Accounting Division/Unit to refer to Sections 7 to 9 of the same COA circular for the procedures in the disposition and derecognition of non-existing/missing PPEs.

Recommendations:
We recommended that Management strictly observe    the regulations on property management as provided under the NGAS Manual and direct:
The Municipal Agriculturist to conduct an annual inventory and submit an inventory report of biological assets;
The Municipal Agriculturist to exert earnest efforts to retrieve the documents related to the distribution, reproduction, and death of the Biological Assets if the assets are nowhere to be found or cannot be located;
The Municipal Agriculturist and the Municipal Accountant to prepare and submit the necessary documents and request for relief from accountability and write-off, if applicable; and
The Municipal Accountant to provide adequate disclosures in the Notes to Financial Statements following IPSAS 27.

Recommendations:
We recommended that Management:
Require the Accountant, the General Services Officer, and the Inventory Committee to follow through the procedures provided in COA Circular 2015-008 for the physical count, reconciliation, recognition, and measurement of infrastructure assets recorded in the registry of public infrastructures;
Require the Municipal Assessor to assist the Municipal Engineer in the assessment of the fair value of the road lot component of local roads under the jurisdiction of the Municipal Government;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to recognize the amount pertaining to the road lot as part of the recorded book value of the road lot as part of the recorded book value of the road network accounts based on the appraised value provided by the Municipal Assessor;
Ensure that the required records and reports are prepared and maintained by both the Accountant and the GSO; and
Submit the required reports and supporting schedules for review and validation to the COA Auditor.

Recommendations:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the following:
HRMO to prioritize updating the salary adjustments or service records of the employees in the GSIS records and provide a timeline to complete the updating of said records;
BAC committee to procure through public bidding the rental of HR electronic software for the use of the Municipality’s HRMO in monitoring, computing, and updating of government remittances to ensure timely remittance from thereon;
Designated ERF Handler to update salary step incremental adjustments of the LGU’s regular and casual employees on the EBCS facility and to reconcile with the GSIS Region 10–Cagayan de Oro Branch Office the noted billing and remittance discrepancies, and
The Municipal Accountant and Treasurer to prioritize the remittance of ₱2,841,202.17 to the GSIS upon reconciliation/updating of the employee records from October 2007 to December 2024.

