The following were recommended:

Ensure that all department heads be required to conduct its own physical count of all properties in their respective department/office based on the MRs and AREs on file at their office and to submit the RPCPPE and Inspection and Inventory of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) to the GSO, if applicable;

Inventory team, to conduct physical count witnessed by the representative of the COA Auditor and GSO, to assign property numbers and provide stickers/ property tags, and prepare the final RPCPPE per type of property, plant and equipment to facilitate reconciliation;

Accordingly, GSO reconcile the balances appearing in the inventory report with the subsidiary ledger records of the accounting to the general ledger so that total valuation of properties appearing in the Trial Balance could be validated as to its existence and accuracy;

General Service Office shall maintain property cards and the Accounting Office shall maintain property ledger cards for each of the Property Plant and Equipment account in order to come up with realistic data of property inventory account; 

Assign full-time office staff of the GSO who will update, maintain and monitor property cards and other records and prepare/ issue the Acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment (ARE) upon receipt/ turnover of property; 

The Inventory Committee to submit the annual Report on the Physical Count of Property Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) to the COA Auditor not later than January 31 of each year; and

The Municipal Accountant to prepare and submit the schedule of depreciation/ lapsing schedule to the COA Auditor.

It was recommended that Management observe strictly the following internal control guidelines on proper recording and management of drugs and medical supplies as provided under the NGAS Manual:

The Municipal Health Officer to: 
Continue the practice of conducting the monthly count of drugs and medicines even without the presence of the DOH Personnel;
Use the Requisition and Issue Slip for issuance of drugs and medicines from the stock room;
Ensure that only authorized personnel are allowed inside the stock room to get medicines;

The MHO and GSO to conduct monthly inventory of drugs and medicines and supplies;

The GSO to prepare Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) and submit to the Municipal Accountant;

The Municipal Accountant to record procurement of drugs and medicines following the perpetual inventory method using the Drugs and Medicines Inventory account and recognize expense for the subsequent issuances based on the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) of the General Services Officer; and

 Management to give feedback or communicate to donor government agencies concerned as soon as they receive any expired or soon to expire medicines from them, for there might be mistake or confusion of the delivered items or the expiry dates may have been overlooked by the donor-government agencies.

